fileChanges.details:
1. The existing calculateStartHeight() walks previousElementSiblings to determine when to switch to fixed. When displayAboveContent is true, the header starts as absolute, so startHeight should be 0 (or the height of preceding siblings like the SEP button). The current logic already handles this correctly because it checks header.previousElementSibling which would be the SEP button (inside the same outer wrapper). No change needed for startHeight.
2. Add a data attribute read: const displayAboveContent = !!parseInt(header.dataset.displayAboveContent, 10);
3. Ensure --header-main-height is set on page load (updateHeaderHeight already does this at init on line 329). This CSS variable is used by the negative margin '-mb-[var(--header-main-height,0px)]' on the outer wrapper.
4. When displayAboveContent is true AND header enters .scrolling state: the CSS classes already switch from absolute to fixed (since .scrolling adds fixed). However, the spacer needs special handling — when displayAboveContent is true, the spacer should NOT be shown because the header was already overlaying content (no layout shift to compensate). Wrap showSpacer() calls in a condition: if (!displayAboveContent) { showSpacer(height); }
5. Similarly, when exiting .scrolling state, hideSpacer() is fine (it's already hidden).
6. Add data-display-above-content attribute to the .header-main div in PHP.
